  "prompt": "Is it a felony to launder money?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is generally considered a felony in most jurisdictions, including the United States. Money laundering involves the process of making illegally-gained proceeds (i.e., \"dirty money\") appear legal (i.e., \"clean\"). This is typically done by disguising the origins of the money, often through a complex sequence of banking transfers or commercial transactions.\n\nIn the United States, money laundering is prosecuted under federal law, primarily through the **Money Laundering Control Act of 1986** (18 U.S.C. \u00a7\u00a7 1956 and 1957). Penalties for money laundering can be severe and may include:\n\n- **Heavy fines**: Up to $500,000 or twice the value of the property involved in the transaction, whichever is greater.\n- **Imprisonment**: Up to **20 years** per count for violations of \u00a7 1956, and up to **10 years** for violations of \u00a7 1957.\n- **Forfeiture**: The government may seize assets involved in or derived from the money laundering activity.\n\nAdditionally, many states have their own laws criminalizing money laundering, which can result in further penalties.\n\nMoney laundering is taken very seriously because it facilitates and enables criminal activities, such as drug trafficking, terrorism, fraud, and organized crime. If you are involved in a situation where money laundering is suspected, it is highly advisable to consult with a legal professional immediately.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
